Statement of Qualifications
Senior Transportation Planner (Temporary Assignment)
Huiyu Lin
1. Education and Experience in Transportation Policy and Planning
I hold a Ph.D. in Geography from Kent State University and a Master of Arts in Geography from SUNY Binghamton, with academic training in transportation planning, Geographic Information Systems (GIS), spatial analysis, and quantitative modeling. My education provided a strong foundation in applying data-driven analysis to transportation planning and policy development.
As a Sustainability Transportation Analyst with Caltrans' Director's Office of Sustainability, I independently develop analytical methodologies and decision-support frameworks that support statewide transportation planning, sustainability, equity, safety, and Vehicle Miles Traveled (VMT) reduction initiatives.
I currently lead the technical development of a statewide Speed Performance research initiative by creating analytical methodologies to identify excessive speeding on the state highway system and support future speed abatement planning, which aligned with the Caltrans Strategic Plan. I also developed analytical methodology and technical documentation for the Corridor Prioritization Tool, a standardized decision-support tool that helps Caltrans Districts prioritize multimodal corridors and determine appropriate planning tiers using data-driven performance measures, aligned with CAPTI. 
I constantly collaborate with many Caltrans Divisions and Offices. For example, I have been actively supporting the implementation of Transportation Equity Index (EQI) in Caltrans various planning processes by designing and developing use cases under the direction of CalSTA to reach the goal of developing an equitable transportation system in California.
These experiences have strengthened my ability to translate transportation policy objectives into practical analytical methodologies that support statewide planning and data-driven decision-making. 
2. Education and Experience with Data Analysis in the Transportation Field, Including GIS and Statistical Software
I have extensive experience applying GIS, programming, and quantitative analysis to transportation planning using ArcGIS Pro, R, Python, SQL, Tableau, StreetLight, and Replica.
At Caltrans, I independently develop analytical workflows that transform complex datasets into repeatable methodologies and practical planning tools. My work includes developing GIS workflows, automating analyses in R, creating performance metrics, integrating multiple statewide datasets, and preparing maps, dashboards, and technical reports for planners and decision-makers.
I developed a GIS and R workflow to conduct spatial and temporal analysis on integrating the Customer Service Requests dataset, EQI, and demographic information. Results identify spatial and temporal patterns of maintenance responses and provide strong data-driven evidence to advance an equitable maintenance resources prioritization process. 
To achieve the goal of improving the quality of life in California, I am conducting research that develops statewide analytical methods and performance metrics to identify excessive speeding using NPRDMS traffic performance data. I also conducted traffic volume analyses using StreetLight and Replica to evaluate historical project performance and support rural VMT reduction initiatives. 
My technical experience allows me to transform transportation data into decision-support tools that improve planning, investment prioritization, and program implementation across Caltrans.
3. Experience with effective communication skills (email, MS Teams, WebEx, phone, in person)
Effective communication is an essential part of my work because nearly every project requires collaboration across multiple Caltrans divisions and technical disciplines.
I regularly communicate with planners, engineers, Subject-Matter-Experts, managers, and executive staff through email, Microsoft Teams, WebEx, phone calls, in-person meetings, technical reports, presentations, and technical documentation. I routinely discuss analytical methodologies, explain technical concepts, incorporate stakeholder feedback, and communicate findings to both technical and non-technical audiences.
My work on EQI implementation requires close collaboration with the Director’s Office of Equity and Tribal Affairs to develop use cases, implementation strategies, and technical guidance. I also collaborate with the VMT Team to evaluate transportation project performance and work with multiple offices to develop analytical methodologies supporting statewide transportation planning initiatives.
In addition, I authored the technical documentation for the Corridor Prioritization Tool to ensure future users can consistently understand and apply the analytical framework. Through these experiences, I have become a trusted technical resource within the Transportation Analysis Branch, helping colleagues translate complex analytical results into practical planning applications that support collaborative, data-driven decision-making.
